<p>Don&#39;t get fooled, in reality we have two African teams here with all the dire consequences this might mean. For one, we have at our hands a defensive nightmare in which scoring the first goal will be key. For another, the best goalkeepers and best defences of this World Cup will do their best to neutralise the attacking prowess of the other team. Unless the coaches do something special in the light of the above observations, we are in for an UNDER 2.5 goals game. What I mean by &#34;something special&#34; here is either practicing set pieces, or practicing long range shots &#40;much like the one Tchuamenie surprised England with&#41;. Once one of the teams manages to score relatively early on &#40;say in the 17th minute like against England&#41;, then we are in for an over 2.5 goals game, because then the other team opens up and will become vulnerable for counterattack. Alternately, we can also go for BTTS after the first early goal.</p>

However, they are poor strategic thinkers. There is a slight chance that Dechamps will come up with something special here, to prevent the usual low scoring African nightmare. If you have ever followed an African Cup, you know what I mean. If you haven&#39;t, then I reason in vain here. LOL</p>
